ollowers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/schiesbn/received_events","type":"user","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2013-11-28t10:14:15z","updated_at":"2013-11-28t10:15:02z","body":"> it would make it much easier to restore previously.\r\n\r\nthis can only be done if a folder structure was deleted, which we already do in the web interface and with sync client 1.5.\r\n\r\nif you delete single files we can't do magic stuff at the trash bin and try to recreate old folder structures again. as said, no other trash bin i'm aware of does such things. if a file gets deleted than the file goes to the trash, if a folder gets deleted than the folder goes to the trash (with his sub files/folder and the correct structure).\r\n\r\nas the sync client fixes are in place and just waiting for the release i close this issue now."}]